Opponent State Inference Under Partial Observability:
An HMM–POMDP Framework for 2026 Formula 1 Energy Strategy
This paper will be updated with Race 1 results and Baum-Welch calibration post-Melbourne.)
Abstract
The 2026 Formula 1 technical regulations introduce a fundamental change to energy strategy: under a 50/50 internal combustion engine / battery power split with unlimited regeneration and a driver-controlled Override Mode (hereafter: Override Mode; abbreviated MOM throughout), the optimal energy deployment policy depends not only on a driver’s own state but on the hidden state of rival cars. This creates a Partially Observable Stochastic Game that cannot be solved by single-agent optimisation methods.
We present a tractable two-layer inference and decision framework. The first layer is a 30-state Hidden Markov Model (HMM) that infers a probability distribution over each rival’s ERS charge level, Override Mode status, and tyre degradation state from five publicly observable telemetry signals. The second layer is a Deep Q-Network (DQN) policy that takes the HMM belief state as input and selects between energy deployment strategies. We formally characterise the counter-harvest trap — a deceptive strategy in which a car deliberately suppresses observable deployment signals to induce a rival into a failed attack — and show that detecting it requires belief-state inference rather than reactive threshold rules.
On synthetic races generated from the model’s own assumptions — a closed evaluation establishing internal consistency prior to empirical validation — the HMM achieves 92.3% ERS inference accuracy (random baseline: 33.3%) and detects counter-harvest trap conditions with 95.7% recall. The HMM belief state closes 88% of the gap between a random classifier and the oracle on ERS inference accuracy. Pre-season analysis reveals substantial circuit-to-circuit variation in recharge availability (1.0 to 2.2 per lap), which creates a circuit-dependent confound for counter-harvest trap detection at energy-scarce circuits; Melbourne represents the hardest-case validation environment, and post-season analysis will test whether detection recall follows the predicted circuit–recharge correlation. This paper constitutes the pre-registered theoretical framework and baseline; empirical calibration on 2026 race telemetry begins with the Australian Grand Prix on 8 March 2026. Code will be made publicly available upon acceptance.
1 Introduction
Formula 1 has always been a game of imperfect information. A driver knows their own tyre temperature, fuel load, and energy reserves exactly; they observe rival positions through timing screens and team radio; but the internal state of a rival’s car — how much battery charge they carry, whether their Override Mode is available or spent, how degraded their tyres are — remains hidden. For most of F1’s history this did not matter strategically: energy deployment was constrained enough that the optimal decision could be computed from own-car state alone.
The 2026 regulations change this (Fédération Internationale de l’Automobile, 2025). The 50/50 power split between internal combustion engine and MGU-K battery places the battery under permanent demand, making energy state a first-order strategic variable every sector. Override Mode is a proximity-gated energy award: when a driver is within one second of the car ahead at the designated detection point, they earn an extra 0.5MJ of deployable energy on the following lap (Fédération Internationale de l’Automobile, 2025). This replaces the function of DRS as a proximity-based overtaking aid — the mechanism changes from a drag-reduction wing to an energy award, but the strategic role is similar. Active Aero replaces the hardware of DRS entirely: the adjustable rear wing is removed and replaced with a driver-controlled binary aero system available only in designated activation zones. Straight-line mode provides mechanical speed independent of ERS deployment, which is the physical basis for the counter-harvest trap. The optimal burn-or-harvest decision in any sector is now a function of the joint state of both cars, not just one’s own.
This paper makes three contributions:
-
1.
Problem formalisation. We formally model 2026 F1 energy management as a Partially Observable Stochastic Game (POSG) (Hansen et al., 2004) and define a tractable POMDP approximation for the single-agent case in which rivals are treated as stationary processes. We precisely characterise the counter-harvest trap — a deceptive equilibrium strategy whose existence motivates the full multi-agent treatment of Papers 2 and 3 in this series.
-
2.
Rival state inference. We propose a 30-state HMM over rival ERS charge level, Override Mode status, and tyre degradation, initialised from an analytically-derived emission matrix and calibrated via Baum-Welch EM on 2026 race telemetry. We identify and document that Override Mode status is inferred primarily through transition dynamics and partially-observable proximity conditions, and that tyre emission signal is concentrated in the cliff degradation state.
-
3.
Decision policy. We propose and fully specify a DQN policy trained on the HMM belief state, and characterise its expected advantages over observable-only threshold baselines under the synthetic evaluation regime. Empirical policy comparison against real-data baselines is deferred to post-Melbourne validation.
Scope and limitations.
This paper treats rivals as stationary processes — their policies do not adapt to our inference. This assumption is violated when rivals reason about being observed, leading to the counter-harvest trap and non-stationary equilibria studied in Paper 2 in this series. We state this limitation at the outset because it is not a defect to be hidden: it is precisely the gap between Paper 1 and Paper 2. The POMDP solution presented here is valuable despite this limitation: it is the correct baseline against which the game-theoretic extension must demonstrate improvement.
2 Background
Prior computational work on F1 strategy has focused on pitstop timing as an optimisation problem (Heilmeier et al., 2020) and on reinforcement learning for race simulation (Betz et al., 2022). These formulations treat energy management as a deterministic sub-problem with known rival actions. Betz et al. (2022) model ERS deployment in hybrid powertrains but in a single-agent setting without rival inference.
The closest structural analogue to the counter-harvest trap in prior work is the Formula E Attack Mode: teams earn a temporary power boost by driving through a designated off-line zone, creating a strategic asymmetry where a car can accept a short-term pace penalty to gain a power advantage (Heilmeier et al., 2020). The key difference from the 2026 counter-harvest trap is that Attack Mode is opt-in from a fixed physical location, publicly visible to all teams, and does not interact with a rival’s inference model — the power boost is simply announced. The 2026 Active Aero system creates a strictly harder version of this problem: the equivalent of Attack Mode can be executed covertly at any activation zone, at a time of the driver’s choosing, in a way that mimics harvesting to an observer without a belief-state model.
To our knowledge no prior work models 2026-specification Override Mode or Active Aero under adversarial conditions.
POMDPs and opponent modelling.
POMDPs (Kaelbling et al., 1998) provide the natural framework for sequential decision-making under state uncertainty. Opponent modelling in multi-agent systems has been approached through Bayesian inference (Albrecht and Stone, 2018), recursive reasoning (Gmytrasiewicz and Doshi, 2005), and game-theoretic agent modelling (Hansen et al., 2004). Our approach is closest to the HMM opponent modelling literature, where a rival’s latent strategy or resource state is inferred from observable actions (Albrecht and Stone, 2018).
HMMs for temporal inference.
HMMs (Rabiner, 1989) are well-suited to the F1 energy inference problem: the hidden state evolves according to known physics (the transition model), and we observe noisy projections of it each sector (the emission model). The Baum-Welch algorithm (Baum et al., 1970) provides maximum-likelihood parameter estimation from unlabelled sequences — critical here because we have no ground-truth labels for rival battery states in real telemetry.
A particle filter could in principle handle continuous ERS charge and relax the conditional independence assumption. We use a discrete HMM for two reasons. First, Baum-Welch provides closed-form maximum-likelihood parameter estimation from unlabelled sequences; particle filters require approximate inference schemes (e.g. SMC-EM) that are substantially less stable at the small data volumes available from a single race weekend. Second, the 3-bin ERS discretisation is physically motivated: the strategic decision is whether a rival can defend (ERSM), cannot defend (ERSL), or has used Override (MOMspent); a continuous representation would require a decision boundary to be learned from data rather than specified from domain knowledge.
HMM identifiability.
With 84,000 emission parameters and 3,480 sector observations per rival per race, the model is unidentifiable from a single race weekend — Baum-Welch estimates from Race 1 are Dirichlet-regularised guesses, not reliable posteriors. By Race 4, cumulative observations reach 13,920, giving a parameter-to-data ratio of approximately 6:1. With parameter tying by (ERS, tyre) cluster reducing to 15 effective emission rows, the ratio improves to 1.5:1 at Race 4, at which point the EM estimates become meaningful. The model should be treated as empirically validated only from Race 4 onwards; Melbourne results are explicitly preliminary under this interpretation.
Deep Q-Networks.
DQN (Mnih et al., 2015) with double Q-learning (van Hasselt et al., 2016) and experience replay (Lin, 1992) provides the policy learning component. We use a deliberately shallow network (three hidden layers, 256–256–128 units) because the belief state does the representational heavy lifting and the training data volume is limited to 3,480 sector observations per car per season.
3 Problem Formalisation
3.1 The 2026 Regulatory Context
The 2026 regulations introduce three strategically relevant changes (Fédération Internationale de l’Automobile, 2025):
50/50 power split.
The total power output is split equally between the internal combustion engine and the MGU-K battery system. Unlike prior hybrid regulations, the battery is under continuous demand, making ERS charge level a first-order strategic variable at every sector rather than only under overtaking.
Override Mode.
A proximity-gated energy award replacing DRS entirely. When a driver is within one second of the car ahead at the lap’s detection point (nominally the final corner), they earn an extra 0.5MJ of deployable energy on the following lap (Fédération Internationale de l’Automobile, 2025). When deployed, Override Mode produces a distinctive speed signature detectable in the speed trap telemetry. Unlike a push-to-pass system, Override Mode is earned through proximity rather than free to use at any time. The strategic value of a deployment depends on whether the rival has sufficient ERS charge to defend against the attack.
Active Aero.
Replaces DRS entirely. Driver-controlled, available only in designated activation zones, with two fixed positions (cornering and straight-line). Straight-line mode in an activation zone produces a speed boost detectable as a positive increment above the ERS-explained baseline. Crucially, a car can run Active Aero in straight-line mode while harvesting (ERSL) — the mechanical downforce reduction provides speed independent of battery deployment. This is the physical basis for the counter-harvest trap (Section 3.3).
Circuit-dependent recharge shortfall.
Pre-season analysis of the 2026 cars reveals that the recharge-per-lap ratio varies from 1.0 at energy-scarce circuits (Australia, Italy, Saudi Arabia) to 2.2 at regen-rich circuits (Azerbaijan, Singapore).111The recharge-per-lap ratios, the 16-second super clipping figure for Australia, and the 250 kW recharge rate are community-derived engineering estimates from pre-season analysis circulating in February 2026. The authors were unable to identify a primary attributable source for these figures; they are not FIA-certified. All downstream claims that depend on them (Sections 5 and 8) should be treated as provisional until confirmed by Race 1 telemetry. At Melbourne specifically, cars require approximately 16 additional seconds of super clipping per lap at 250 kW to approach the energy ceiling imposed by the 50/50 power split. The MGU-K battery capacity is approximately 4 MJ (at 350 kW peak discharge rate, the battery depletes in 11.4 s); at 250 kW over 16 s this represents a full extra battery cycle beyond what natural regen provides. This transforms super clipping from a discretionary tool into a near-mandatory operating mode at certain circuits, with direct consequences for the counter-harvest trap’s observability discussed in Section 3.3.
