3.3 The Counter-Harvest Trap
The central motivating phenomenon of this paper is:
Definition 7 (Counter-Harvest Trap).
A deceptive strategy for a car ahead (Car B) against a following car (Car A) in which Car B simultaneously: (i) runs ERS in harvest mode (ERSL, conserving charge); (ii) deploys Active Aero in straight-line mode within an activation zone (maintaining straight-line speed despite harvesting); and (iii) allows the observable telemetry signals to indicate harvesting. Car A’s inference model identifies the ERSL signature as an attack opportunity and burns energy. Car B then activates full deployment (including Override Mode), defending the position easily because it has the full energy reserve that Car A just spent.
The trigger signature exploits a key 2026 regulatory asymmetry: lift-and-coast disables active aero, but super clipping does not. Super clipping is the automated redirection of ICE power to the battery at full throttle; the car slows slightly (power diverted from the rear wheels) but active aero remains deployed (Fédération Internationale de l’Automobile, 2025).
The counter-harvest trap therefore has a precise observable signature: (Active Aero deployed, consistent with full throttle) combined with far below what committed Active Aero deployment with full energy would produce. A car genuinely attacking with Active Aero deployed produces km/h; the trap car produces only km/h, indistinguishable from ERSM without Active Aero to an observer who does not track . A rival observing only sees km/h and interprets this as moderate energy state and no attack opportunity; in reality the battery is filling and the Active Aero is concealing it. A model without Active Aero as an explicit observable cannot distinguish super clipping from genuine ERSL without deception.
Proposition 1.
The counter-harvest trap is not detectable by a single-observable threshold policy on alone.
