Circuit-dependent trap distinguishability.
The diagnostic power of the with depressed signature depends on that combination being unusual — its rarity is what gives it discriminatory value. This assumption holds at regen-rich circuits but breaks down at energy-scarce ones.
At circuits where super clipping is mandatory for approximately 16 seconds per lap (Section 3.3), the active super-clipping speed penalty is large enough that during straight-line phases is the expected modal state of every car on the grid, regardless of strategic intent. In this regime, even the corrected trap signature — with depressed — becomes ambient: every car running Active Aero while super-clipping produces exactly this pattern. The combination is therefore ambient rather than diagnostic at circuits like Australia.
The rolling 5-lap baseline provides a partial rescue. Since all cars are super clipping in the same track sections, the baseline adapts and treats mandatory super clipping as the new normal. A car that has conserved energy and avoided super clipping will still produce a positive relative to the super-clipping field. The baseline-delta design therefore partially preserves signal even under universal super clipping, but the margin for detecting deliberate deception narrows considerably relative to regen-rich circuits.
The implication is that trap detection confidence is circuit-dependent, correlated with the recharge-per-lap ratio. At Azerbaijan (ratio 2.2), super clipping is rare and the signature retains strong diagnostic value. At Australia (ratio 1.0), the same signature is the default operating condition and the trap becomes substantially harder to distinguish from normal racing. This generates a testable prediction: trap detection recall should be lower at Australia than the synthetic baseline of 95.7%, and should improve at higher-regen circuits later in the season.
Critically, this circuit dependence does not invalidate the framework — it refines the conditions under which the counter-harvest trap is a viable strategic tool. We conjecture that a rational trap-setter prefers high-regen circuits, where their deception operates against a cleaner background signal and the with depressed combination retains diagnostic rarity. Whether this conjecture holds depends on a non-trivial game-theoretic question: at high-regen circuits the defender’s HMM also operates with cleaner signal and tracks ERS state more accurately, potentially making the trap harder to execute as well as easier to detect. Resolving this requires the multi-agent analysis of Paper 2; we present the circuit-dependence observation as empirical motivation rather than a settled strategic prediction. At low-regen circuits, the signal confusion is symmetric: both attacker and defender operate with degraded information, and the advantage shifts to whichever car manages its energy state more reliably over a stint.
