On the information bottleneck.
The DQN receives the HMM belief state rather than raw observables (, ). This is theoretically correct: in a POMDP, the belief state is a sufficient statistic of the entire observation history. Given correct HMM parameters, the policy loses no information by operating on rather than the raw signal; in practice, however, an incorrect or surprised HMM produces a biased , and the DQN then acts on that bias with no direct corrective — specifically, the residuals the HMM could not explain are not visible to the policy. End-to-end learning directly from raw observables to actions was considered but rejected in favour of POMDP coherence and interpretability: passing raw observables alongside would double-count evidence already integrated into the belief state, violating the sufficient-statistic property. Two partial mitigations are in place: (1) the input provides a raw, HMM-independent signal for closure rate; and (2) trap detection is explicitly computed as a function of and the zone flag, not a raw-signal threshold. A richer architecture that handles HMM residuals explicitly is deferred to Paper 2.
6 Dataset
6.1 Data Source
Race telemetry is retrieved via the FastF1 Python library (Schaefer, 2020), which provides access to the official FOM timing and telemetry feed at 10 Hz sampling. The car_data endpoint provides per-car speed, throttle, and braking data at sector resolution, available for race sessions from 2018 onwards.
6.2 Observable Derivation
All five observables are computed as deviations from a per-driver rolling 5-lap baseline. The fuel exclusion is justified quantitatively: at 1.5 kg/lap over a 58-lap race, fuel burn produces a monotonic pace improvement of approximately 0.03 s/lap. This per-lap drift falls well within the s emission noise; cumulative drift over the 5-lap baseline window ( s) is absorbed by the rolling baseline itself, which tracks the monotone trend and subtracts it from each observation.
6.3 Dataset Statistics
Race coverage statistics will be reported after the 2026 Australian Grand Prix (March 8, 2026). All synthetic experiments use 20 simulated races at 174 sectors each (3,480 total sector observations).
7 Closed-Loop Synthetic Validation
7.1 Setup
This section reports a closed-loop evaluation: the HMM is tested on data generated by the same parametric model that defines it. This is deliberately circular. It verifies that the components work together as designed — that the forward algorithm correctly recovers states whose transitions and emissions were set analytically — but it does not constitute empirical validation. The synthetic generative process assumes the same conditional independence as the HMM, the same emission distributions, and the same transition matrices. Performance here is therefore an upper bound on real-data performance, not an estimate of it. Empirical validation begins with Race 1 data on 8 March 2026.
The generative model, strategy profiles, and observation noise specification are fully documented in Appendix E. In brief: 20 synthetic races are generated (5 per strategy profile: aggressive, conservative, trap-setter, balanced) using the physics-derived transition matrices with i.i.d. Gaussian noise added to each continuous observable ( km/h for , s for , m for ). The HMM receives these noisy observations and is evaluated against the known ground-truth states.
We evaluate three capabilities: (i) HMM belief accuracy on synthetic races; (ii) HMM calibration on real 2026 race data, beginning with the Australian Grand Prix; (iii) policy performance of all four baselines in simulation.
