7.2 HMM Inference Accuracy (Synthetic)
Under internal consistency evaluation, ERS inference accuracy of 92.3% confirms the strong emission signal from and within the model’s own parametric assumptions. The HMM closes 88% of the gap between a random classifier (33.3%) and the oracle (100%) on ERS level — a gap that is itself an artefact of the 3-bin state design and should not be interpreted as an absolute performance claim.
Override Mode accuracy of 67.3% (random baseline: 50.0%) reflects the 2-state nature of the problem. The dominant error source is uncertainty about whether the proximity condition was met on the previous lap when timing data is incomplete. Trap detection recall of 95.7% on 117 trap sectors confirms the joint signature is internally discriminative — consistent with Proposition 1’s claim that belief-state inference is necessary for trap detection. False negative analysis shows the 4.3% missed traps concentrate in sectors where (trap executed outside activation zones), which is outside the formal trap definition (Definition 7).
ECE of 0.11 indicates mild over-confidence under the synthetic regime. This is a lower bound on real-data calibration error: the synthetic generative model assumes the same conditional independence as the HMM, so the 0.11 reflects only discretisation artefacts rather than the mechanical correlations between , , and present in real telemetry. Real-data ECE is expected to be substantially higher; post-Melbourne calibration results will be reported after Race 1.
