8 Discussion
What the system does well.
ERS state inference from and is robust. Counter-harvest trap detection is the clearest strength of the full system over the observable-only baseline: the joint signature is identifiable in a way that no scalar threshold can replicate.
The stationary opponent assumption.
The most important limitation is structural. We model rivals as stationary processes that do not adapt their strategy based on being observed. The POMDP policy trained here is the correct baseline and the floor, not the ceiling, of performance under adversarial conditions. Paper 2 formalises why no stationary strategy achieves Nash equilibrium under these conditions.
Calibration.
The conditional independence assumption produces over-confident beliefs. ECE on synthetic data is a lower bound on real-data calibration error. Post-Baum-Welch calibration on real data will partially improve this, but will not fully correct for the structural violation.
Data regime.
At 24:1 parameter-to-data ratio after one race, the Baum-Welch estimates are Dirichlet-regularised guesses. The model should be treated as empirically validated only from Race 4 onwards.
Mid-season non-stationarity.
The alternating schedule handles gradual parameter drift but not sudden step-changes. Detection of a step-change is possible via log-likelihood monitoring on race-day data.
Transition matrix sector averaging.
The global and matrices are population averages across track geometry. The pre-season recharge data makes this a structural issue: the to circuit spread is not captured by the sector one-hot at all. Circuit-conditioned transition matrices are the correct fix and are deferred to Paper 2.
Override Mode prior.
The prior governs Override Mode recovery when live timing data is incomplete. This single scalar is a deliberate simplification: the true earn probability varies substantially by race position, stint phase, and circuit. The residual limitation is distinct: we observe the ego car’s gap to the rival, but Override Mode depends on the rival’s gap to the car ahead of the rival. This update is already implemented in the Melbourne pipeline: the FOM live timing feed provides per-car sector intervals at each timing line, allowing to be conditioned on the rival’s observed gap to the car immediately ahead of them and updated near-deterministically at each sector boundary, reducing the residual dependence on the 0.25 scalar prior to the subset of laps where timing data is genuinely absent.
Super clipping as a candidate sixth observable.
The 16-second mandatory super clipping duration at Australia is itself a potentially observable quantity via the throttle channel of FastF1 car_data. A super clipping duration observable would require a separate derivation preserving the acceleration residual, distinct from the existing pipeline. We flag this as a post-Melbourne investigation item.
9 Conclusion
We have presented a tractable two-layer framework for opponent state inference and decision-making in 2026 Formula 1 energy strategy. The 30-state HMM provides belief states over rival ERS charge, Override Mode status, and tyre degradation from publicly observable telemetry signals, with a DQN policy trained on those belief states to select energy deployment actions. The framework formally characterises and detects the counter-harvest trap — a deceptive strategy enabled by the 2026 Active Aero system — which no single-signal threshold policy can reliably identify.
The stationary opponent assumption made here is precisely what Paper 2 in this series breaks: we prove that no stationary strategy achieves Nash equilibrium under energy depletion non-stationarity, and that the counter-harvest trap exists as a game-theoretic solution concept. Paper 3 proposes a tractable approximate solution via Partially Observable Monte Carlo Tree Search with bounded rationality.
